      "role": "user",
      "content": "hey, i'm looking at my student loan amortization schedule and i'm kinda confused. i've been making my monthly payments on time every month but the principal balance is barely even going down. can you explain how the interest actually gets calculated each month? like, why does it feel like so much of my money is just disappearing instead of hitting the actual loan amount?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "That is a very common feeling, and it's almost exactly what happens when you try to pay off a loan with a standard amortization schedule, which is basically a math trick designed to make the loan last a long time.\n\nThink of your loan balance like a giant pile of gold coins, and the interest is a tiny, invisible goblin that sits on top of that pile every single month. That goblin doesn't just eat your gold; it actually *creates* more gold by eating a tiny slice of what you already have. So, when you make your monthly payment, the goblin gets paid first from your money before you can even touch the principal.\n\nHere is the breakdown of why your principal barely moves:\n\n1.  **The Goblins Eat First:** Every month, the lender calculates the interest based on the *current* balance. If you have a huge balance, the goblins are very hungry and eat a big chunk of your payment.\n2.  **The Principal is the Leftover:** Only the money left over after the goblins are fed goes toward actually reducing the principal. In the early years, that \"leftover\" is a tiny fraction of your payment.\n3.  **The G",
